\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator indicated that criteria 1\'2C 3\'2C 4\'2C and 7 do not comply with minimum standards while the remainder are all in need of improvement. \line \line The evaluator noted that\'2C significantly\'2C this submission contains no evidence that this programme has been developed with the support\'2C or in support of the South African Tourism industry - there is no information from any tourism related stakeholder\'2C that this programme has their support\'2C and that it has been designed along their needs\'2C or knowledge and skills required by the Tourism industry. It must also be noted that neither the National Destination Marketing Organization \'28South African Tourism\'29\'2C the South African Tourism Services Association \'28SATSA\'29\'2C the Southern African Association of Conference Industry \'28SAACI\'29\'2C Gauteng Tourism\'2C nor the Tourism Business Council of South Africa \'28TBCSA\'29 has provided any support for this programme. It is therefore evident that the programme has been designed in isolation. \line \line The minimum credit requirements for a qualification at NQF level 5 is 120 credits. This programme exceeds that minimum requirement substantially\'2C by 30 credits. Of concern is the fact that there is no consistency with the credits values for the various modules. It ranges from 8 to 20 credits. It creates the perception that this programme was designed in a haphazard manner with not much thought for consistency\'2C balance and logic. In discussing the modules the evaluator points out some of the structural flaws of the programme which impair the programme\'27s intellectual credibility.\line \line The evaluator furthermore draws attention to the fact that none of the policies submitted make any specific reference to dealing with distance learning students as a particular market segment. Catering for the needs of distance learning students is somewhat different to that of contact students and therefore policies must be designed and approved to include this aspect\'2C that is\'2C distance learning. Where will the assessment of the distance learning students take place if they have to sit for any assessment\'3F Details pertaining to this issue could not be determined. Since the programme will be offered via distance learning\'2C the infrastructural needs may be less. In other words\'2C there may not be a need for lecture venues\'2C and assuming that all distance learning students will have access to their own computers to complete the module on PC Environment and Applications 2. \line \line The admission requirements are at best vague. It only stipulates a \'E2\'80\'9C30\'25 minimum in the language of teaching and learning \'28English\'29\'2C which is a Level 2 pass at Grade 12.\'22 Furthermore\'2C it does not stipulate whether there are other requirements\'2C e.g.  Level 3 for Mathematics Literacy.  The enrolment plan is equally problematic in the sense that it does not take the realities of the market sector into account. It is envisaged that 100 students will be enrolled in the first year and this will be increased to 1000. \line \line Academic staffing is also seen as a major constraint. Of concern is the fact that the programme coordinator has no experience in Tourism teaching and learning\'2C and is in fact an academic administrator. Although this programme is not being offered as yet\'2C it would be expected that a suitable programme coordinator would drive the process at this stage\'2C albeit in a temporary capacity. \line \line A major concern is the library facility\'2C specifically for the proposed Tourism programme. The BCC library only has two tourism titles\'2C or books at this stage.  \line \line The Directorate concurs with the recommendation that the programme cannot be accredited.\line \line \line \cell \pard 

